insta_description:
Thinking back to this encounter with a rarely seen group of California Transient/ Biggs killer whales. 6 of these apex predators were found in the Santa Barbara channel last April aboard the @condorexpresssb When we first found them, they were eating what appeared to be a sea lion carcass and began harassing 3 humpback whales. The humpbacks appeared to have fresh injuries from these killer whales. This female has not been given a catalog/ ID number and looks as if she were a sprouting male. However over the years her triangular pizza slice shaped fin has stayed the same. She travels with another female from the CA122 matriline, and may be related to CA122 in some way. She travels with a newly born calf of her own as well as a juvenile. They can be easily identified by their strange triangular dorsal fins, and extremely large eyepatches! ‚Äî These mysterious outer coast transients lead unique lives that are not very well known. Where do they go when they‚Äôre not spotted? How far out to sea to they go? Hopefully time, more research, and a shared knowledge and appreciation of these charismatic creatures will tell. 
Photos by @adam_ernster 
Aboard @condorexpresssb .

Saying goodbye to social media for awhile as this year is just turning out to be too much for me personally and unfortunately social media exacerbates things, especially during times like this. So I‚Äôm going to withdraw because that‚Äôs the only way I know how to deal with myself and try to get back into that mindset I had when living out alone in the remote wilderness of Idaho. I felt free then, and knew I would never get to experience that again and here I am feeling more alone than ever in an area that prides itself in high-tech future forward development, yet humanity is behaving just as primitive as ever. So time to just take a step back and observe how this all unfolds. 
Hope everyone stays healthy and safe out there.

Pacific sea nettle (Chrysaora fuscescens) or West Coast sea nettle, is a native to the eastern Pacific Ocean from Canada to Mexico.  It's long tentacles and frilly mouth-arms are covered with stinging cells to paralyze drifting animals, then bring the helpless prey to the mouth, where it's digested. 
These beautiful, mesmerizing specimens are on exhibit at the Monterrey Bay Aquarium.

insta_description:
@guerillatacos #guerillatacos
As restaurants throughout Los Angeles pivot to takeout or delivery-only models during the novel coronavirus pandemic, Guerrilla Tacos just announced an offer that could only happen in Southern California: tacos and toilet paper ‚Äî all in one. Chef Wes Avila created an emergency taco kit for his #ArtsDistrict restaurant that not only includes all the necessary fixings for a four-person taco dinner, it also comes with four rolls of toilet paper, a nod to the runs on grocery stores and hoarding that has been going on across the country.

The $150 kit can be ordered from the Guerrilla Tacos website and picked up through a window at the restaurant. Every order includes four rolls of toilet paper, five pounds of roasted chicken, five pounds of carne asada, a quart red salsa, a quart green salsa, tortillas, onion, cilantro, rice, beans, and 30 eggs.

Avila‚Äôs taco kit arrives within hours of Los Angeles County and City of Los Angeles officials announcing a countywide closure of restaurants and bars, except for takeout and delivery. This directive impacts over 10 million residents and businesses across 88 incorporated cities and countless unincorporated areas outside of the city of Los Angeles. For those who decide to try to ride out the pandemic by offering delivery and takeout ‚Äî instead of just closing, as many are ‚Äî the move may be to continue to think of innovative ways to make, sell, and market their food. Last week, West Hollywood‚Äôs Employees Only created a cocktail making kit via delivery, and Four Cafe in Eagle Rock is also adding toilet paper to delivery orders

@ikepyunüíó. A little story of positive engagement. Friends, during this time you may have an elderly neighbor or seniors in your community that might need a little help with groceries. Step in and help with an extra hand if you can. Always safely and with love üåà. Xx ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢ ‚Ä¢
Los Angeles, California

Tonight, as I pulled into my building, I saw an elderly neighbor of mine looking really upset.¬†¬†I asked her if she was ok and she explained that she had just walked back from the grocery store and couldn‚Äôt find any food or toilet paper for her and her husband.‚Å£
‚Å£
Having seen her many times pushing her disabled husband on a wheelchair around the neighborhood, I knew I had to help her.‚Å£
‚Å£
I asked her to make me a shopping list and told her I‚Äôd come by to pick it up.¬†¬†When I stopped by, she handed me this short list and I asked why she didn‚Äôt write more.¬†¬†She said that she was just so thankful that someone was helping her and she didn‚Äôt want burden me with a long list.‚Å£
‚Å£
It took me 4 different stops to get everything on her list (plus extras) but it just made me realize first hand how difficult we make it for the elderly to get what they need.‚Å£
‚Å£
Let‚Äôs help our elderly neighbors and see if they need any assistance picking up groceries or medication‚Ä¶ and stop hoarding all the toilet paper!

accessibility_caption: Photo by Nixtaco Mexican Kitchen ¬Æ in Nixtaco Mexican Kitchen with @visitplacer, @culinary.chris, @sacfoodreview, @sacviews, and @eatswithmandy. Image may contain: possible text that says 'TAKE OUT AND DELIVERY ONLY E ORDER ONLINE OR CALL www.nixta.co NO ‰∏Ω'
insta_description:
We feel like even though the authorities haven't shut us down we have the social responsibility to make the incredibly difficult decision of TEMPORARILY closing our dining room for dine-in service in order to prioritize the safety of our team, guests, and in the interest of general public health.

Effective tomorrow Tuesday March 17th we will be offering ONLINE ORDERS and CALLS for pick-up and delivery, as well as TAKE-OUT orders at the restaurant.  We encourage everyone to stay home and keep social distance as indicated by the authorities... The sooner we do this, the sooner we go back to a normal life. 
This is a really tough call, and many of our staff will be affected; some of them have volunteered to take on delivery driver roles, so please keep us in mind for your delivery options. 
Also starting tomorrow, we will be offering more than ‚Äútraditional restaurant fare‚Äù. We are trying to implement ways to solve your potential needs. We have access to food service deliveries every day from our local vendors. And they want to help us help you. So, bear with us, we will soon publish a list of household staples at market prices, that will help us serve you as a one-stop-shop. Also, we have started packing all our meats in 1lb vacuum packed bags, ready to be reheated, stored in the fridge up to a week, or frozen up to 6 months‚Ä¶ 
We are here for you.

#supportlocal #shoplocal #sacramento #California

accessibility_caption: Photo by Denni George in Griffith Observatory. Image may contain: sky, night and outdoor
insta_description:
Ominous, under the moonlit sky sat Griffith Observatory, the dead air of the night sky punctuated by the no-sound of wind, as if to portent the arrival of some foul otherworldly master of the cosmos, who were leviathans compared to humans. Our puny physical world seemed like a whirlpool in the shower drain to them. Our galaxy, a small cheerio, hidden amongst a haystack of other galaxies, that the only reason these superior terrors never posed a threat to us, was due to how much of a needle in the haystack we were. What kept us from apocalypse was our microscopic size. We were too tiny, too puny for them to notice us. That was about to end tonight. .

accessibility_caption: Photo by Kevin Keyüîë Photography üåµüì∑‚õ∫üååüëÄüßÇüåä in Clark Dry Lake. Image may contain: sky, outdoor, nature and water
insta_description:
Starry Night Over Clark Dry Lake in Wet Mode.

Well, the lake isn't so dry lately due to an abnormally high level of rain in the Anza-Borrego Desert. This is the most water I've ever seen in this area. Normally this is a typical dry lake bed with big cracks in the dirt.

I had hoped the water and wind would calm down so I could get some amazing reflections, but both kept moving - except for some very shallow portions of water in the foreground.

This is about 117 minutes total exposure time shot at f/4.5 and ISO 1250 with a Canon EOS R and Canon 17-40mm f/4L lens.

üá¨üáßMono Lake is a large, shallow saltwater lake located in Mono County, California. It was formed at least 760,000 years ago as a terminal lake of a landlocked basin. The lake has a high level of salts that make its water alkaline. It also has high levels of arsenic.
Did you know that? NASA has identified a bacterium (GFAJ-1) in the lake, a class of Gammaproteobacteria whose diet is low in phosphorus and rich in arsenic. This is a discovery of great scientific interest, as it is the first known organism that can build its cellular components using a chemical that is poisonous to anyone else.
.

Founded in 1881 as a silver mining town, it is now a state park called Calico Ghost Town. Giant letters with the name of the town welcome us. Walter Knott acquired Calico in the 1950's and restored all the buildings in the town, except for 5 of them which remain with their original architecture, to look like the 1880's.

üá¨üáßBadwater is an endorheic basin located in Death Valley National Park. It stands out as the lowest point in North America, with a depth of 86 m below sea level. The water forms temporary lakes after storms, the water evaporates, the minerals concentrate and only the salts remain.

.

¬øSab√≠as que? Esta especie de pez tiene la capacidad de sobrevivir en el agua desde temperaturas cercanas al punto de congelaci√≥n hasta casi 108¬∞F/42¬∞C, adem√°s de en agua 4 veces m√°s salada que el oc√©ano. Con el calor del verano, los peces se quedan dormidos.

üá¨üáßIn Salt Creek, where fresh water became salt water when the giant lake dried up about 10,000 years ago, we can find the curious Salt Creek pupfish, a 2 inch long fish that lives nowhere else.
Did you know that? This species of fish has the ability to survive in water from near-freezing temperatures up to about 108¬∞F/42¬∞C, as well as in water 4 times saltier than the ocean. In the heat of summer, fish fall asleep.
.
‚îÖ It is very curious to see these small fish swimming quietly in a kind of pond in the middle of the desert, do not miss them if you visit Death Valley. And you? Have you lived something unique with the fauna in one of your trips? ‚îÖ

¬øSab√≠as que? El b√≥rax es un mineral que se encuentra principalmente en dos lugares del planeta: Turqu√≠a y el desierto de California.
.
‚îÖ Cuando viajo, me encanta conocer datos hist√≥ricos del lugar que visito e imaginarme c√≥mo ser√≠a el d√≠a a d√≠a de todas esas personas. ¬øY vosotr@s? ¬øOs gusta dejar volar vuestra imaginaci√≥n cuando viaj√°is? ‚îÖ

üá¨üáßInside Death Valley National Park, in the Furnace Creek Museum, we can find a stagecoach, mining and transportation equipment, one of the only two original surviving wagons of the Team of Twenty Mules, artifacts from the days of the pioneers, Old Dinah (a steam tractor and wagon that replaced the Twenty Mule Teams), and a Baldwin 280 Death Valley mining era locomotive, 1885-1927, historic locomotive used to transport borax.

üá™üá∏Para que las dunas existan debe haber una fuente de arena, vientos dominantes que la muevan y un lugar para que se recoja. S√≥lo hay unas pocas zonas en Death Valley en las que la arena est√° "atrapada" por accidentes geogr√°ficos como las monta√±as. Las Mesquite Flat Sand Dunes son las m√°s conocidas y f√°ciles de visitar, localizadas cerca de Stovepipe Wells. Aunque la duna m√°s alta se eleva s√≥lo unos 30 m. (100 pies), las dunas cubren una vasta √°rea. Este campo de dunas incluye tres tipos: crecientes, lineales y en forma de estrella.
¬øSab√≠as que? El sandboarding s√≥lo est√° permitido en las dunas de Mesquite y prohibido en el resto de dunas para proteger plantas y animales sensibles.
.
‚îÖ La imagen de desierto que tenemos con dunas dista mucho de Death Valley, hasta que llegamos a este punto, donde el paisaje cambia. ¬øQu√© os parece? ¬øOs gusta el desierto? ‚îÖ
‚úàÔ∏é ‚úàÔ∏é ‚úàÔ∏é ‚úàÔ∏é ‚úàÔ∏é ‚úàÔ∏é ‚úàÔ∏é ‚úàÔ∏é ‚úàÔ∏é ‚úàÔ∏é ‚úàÔ∏é ‚úàÔ∏é ‚úàÔ∏é ‚úàÔ∏é ‚úàÔ∏é
üá¨üáß For the dunes to exist there must be a source of sand, dominant winds to move it and a place for it to be collected. There are only a few areas in Death Valley where the sand is "trapped" by geographical features such as mountains. The Mesquite Flat Sand Dunes are the best known and easiest to visit, located near Stovepipe Wells. Although the highest dune rises only about 30 m. (100 feet), the dunes cover a vast area. This field of dunes includes three types: crescent, linear and star-shaped.
Did you know that? Sandboarding is only allowed on the Mesquite dunes and prohibited on the other dunes to protect sensitive plants and animals.
.
‚îÖ The image of desert we have with dunes is far from Death Valley, until we get to this point, where the landscape changes. What do you think? Do you like the desert? ‚îÖ

insta_description:
Yosemite National Park
‚†Ä
The park is located among the mountains in central California, at an altitude of more than 1200 meters and has 5 climatic zones. It covers an area of ‚Äã‚Äã3081 km¬≤ and is located on the western slopes of the Sierra Nevada mountain range. Yosemite National Park was founded in 1890. It is famous for its many very beautiful waterfalls and dense pine forests. This is one of the most attractive attractions in America. The park is magnificent in all four seasons. In winter, everything is hidden under a thick snow cover. Spring is especially romantic, as everything blooms and turns green, and the air is filled with all kinds of aromas. Summer is very green and offers a pleasant coolness that is hard to find in California during the summer months. In the fall, the park is magnificent. Golden leaves fall into the mirror surface of the ponds, but most of the waterfalls are completely dry. Black bears, deer, squirrels, eagles and many other forest inhabitants live quietly here.

Coit Tower. San Francisco.
---
Coit Tower is a 210-foot (64 m) tower in the Telegraph Hill neighborhood of San Francisco, California, offering panoramic views over the city and the bay. The tower, in the city's Pioneer Park, was built between 1932 and 1933 using Lillie Hitchcock Coit's bequest to beautify the city of San Francisco. It was added to the National Register of Historic Places on January 29, 2008.

insta_description:
Everglades National Park
‚†Ä
The Everglades National Park is Florida's largest, most southerly tropical region, which is mostly occupied by swamps and flooded deciduous forests. The area of ‚Äã‚Äãthis largest park is one and a half million acres. It is here that you can find rare specimens of fauna and see animals that have long been considered endangered.
‚†Ä
Here you will find animals such as the Bald Eagle, various species of herons and the largest cat after the tiger and lion - the puma. But the owner of these areas is undoubtedly an alligator. This is a kind of North American crocodile that lives in these areas. People and pets should be careful, as they can easily become its prey. In the Everglades Park, you will also see a strange animal, which, unlike the alligator, is known for its gentle and calm temperament - a water cow, known as a sea cow.
The Everglades National Park is a UNESCO World Heritage Site. The park was founded in 1934.

insta_description:
Yellowstone National Park
‚†Ä
Situated among the Rocky Mountains of Wyoming, Montana, and Idaho, Yellowstone National Park is one of the symbols of the United States. It was founded in 1872 and since 1978 is included in the UNESCO World Heritage List. With its untouched, typical North American nature, Yellowstone will make you feel the years when the first Europeans appeared on the continent.
Pine forests, lakes, rivers, canyons, caves, waterfalls and geysers form a colorful palette of this magical paradise.
Yellowstone Lake, one of the largest alpine lakes in North America, is located in the center of the Yellowstone Caldera, the largest supervolcano on the continent.
Yellowstone Volcano - super volcano, megavolcano. It is located in Yellowstone National Park. For several years now, the world has been excited by the news that it is about to wake up, a catastrophe will happen, America will end, and the world will plunge into a nuclear winter. While the supervolcano is sleeping.
The park is home to animal species such as the grizzly bear, black bear, bald eagle, puma, deer, bison and many other wildlife. There are hundreds of geysers in Yellowstone, but the Old Faithful geyser is the most worthy, which can release hot water more than 50 meters above the ground during an eruption!
